About Emily


Environmental Data Scientist ‚Ä¢ Artist ‚Ä¢ Researcher




Background


I am passionate about using data science to solve environmental challenges while maintaining a deep commitment to the human stories behind the numbers. I believe that the most powerful research emerges from the intersection of technical rigor, creative thinking, and genuine care for the communities we serve.


Currently pursuing a PhD in Environmental Data Science at UCSB, my research focuses on developing machine learning models to analyze satellite imagery and track environmental changes across Sub-Saharan Africa. I am particularly interested in applying these tools to biodiversity conservation, wildlife corridor mapping, and indigenous land rights monitoring.


Beyond the laboratory, I maintain an active creative practice and community involvement, organizing environmental initiatives and exploring how data-driven insights can translate into meaningful environmental action.




Academic Journey


My academic journey began with a focus on pure mathematics, drawn to the elegance and precision of numerical analysis. I discovered that mathematics could be applied to address real-world challenges ‚Äî from tracking deforestation patterns to predicting climate trends and understanding human-environment interactions.


